    Qed.
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of \Phi)
  n \NATmul m is equal to m \NATmul n
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number and v1 \NATmul v0 is equal to \NATzero then (v1 is equal to \NATzero or v0 is equal to \NATzero)))
Proof:
  it is wrong that n is equal to \NATzero and it is wrong that m is equal to \NATzero
  m' is a natural number and n' is a natural number and (n is equal to n' \NATplus \NATone and m is equal to m' \NATplus \NATone)
  \NATzero is equal to n \NATmul m and n \NATmul m is equal to n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus \NATone and n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus \NATone is equal to n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus n' \NATplus \NATone and n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus n' \NATplus \NATone is equal to n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus n' \NATplus \NATone
  Proof:
    n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus \NATone is equal to n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul m' \NATplus n' \NATplus \NATone
  Qed.
  for some v0, (v0 is a natural number and \NATzero is equal to v0 \NATplus \NATone)
  falsity holds
Qed.

Theorem (right_cancellability_of_multiplication):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if it is wrong that v0 is equal to \NATzero then (if v2 \NATmul v0 is equal to v1 \NATmul v0 then v2 is equal to v1)))))
Proof:
  \Phi is a class and (if \Nat is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \Nat and v0 is an object and for all v1, (if v1 is an element of \Nat then (if v0 \NATmul k is equal to v1 \NATmul k and it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero then v0 is equal to v1))))
  \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  Proof:
    m' is an element of \Nat
    \NATzero \NATmul k is equal to m' \NATmul k and it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero
    m' \NATmul k is equal to \NATzero
    m' is equal to \NATzero or k is equal to \NATzero
    m' is equal to \NATzero
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi)
  Proof:
    n' is an element of \Phi
    for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Nat then (if n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to v0 \NATmul k and it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero then n' \NATplus \NATone is equal to v0))
    Proof:
      m' is an element of \Nat
      n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to m' \NATmul k and it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero
      if m' is equal to \NATzero then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to \NATzero
        n' \NATplus \NATone is equal to \NATzero
        falsity holds
      Qed.
      if it is wrong that m' is equal to \NATzero then the thesis holds
      Proof:
        l is a natural number and m' is equal to l \NATplus \NATone
        n' \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to l \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k
        n' \NATmul k \NATplus k is equal to n' \NATmul k \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k and n' \NATmul k \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to n' \NATmul k \NATplus k and n' \NATmul k \NATplus k is equal to l \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k and l \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to l \NATmul k \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k and l \NATmul k \NATplus \NATone \NATmul k is equal to l \NATmul k \NATplus k
        n' \NATmul k is equal to l \NATmul k
        Proof:
          n' \NATmul k is a natural number and l \NATmul k is a natural number
        Qed.
        n' is equal to l
        Proof:
          if n' \NATmul k is equal to l \NATmul k and it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero then n' is equal to l
        Qed.
        n' \NATplus \NATone is equal to l \NATplus \NATone and l \NATplus \NATone is equal to m'
      Qed.
    Qed.
    n' \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is a natural number then v0 is an element of \Phi)
  if n \NATmul k is equal to m \NATmul k then n is equal to m
Qed.

Theorem (left_cancellability_of_multiplication):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if it is wrong that v0 is equal to \NATzero then (if v0 \NATmul v2 is equal to v0 \NATmul v1 then v2 is equal to v1)))))
