Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v1 \NATless v0 and v0 \NATleq v1 \NATplus \NATone then v0 is equal to v1 \NATplus \NATone)))
Proof:
  n \NATless m and m \NATleq n \NATplus \NATone
  k is a natural number and k is positive and m is equal to n \NATplus k
  l is a natural number and n \NATplus \NATone is equal to m \NATplus l
  n \NATplus \NATone is equal to m \NATplus l and m \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l and n \NATplus k \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l
  k \NATplus l is equal to \NATone
  l is equal to \NATzero
  Proof:
    it is wrong that the thesis holds
    \NATzero \NATless k and \NATzero \NATless l
    if k is equal to \NATone and l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      k \NATplus l is equal to \NATtwo and it is wrong that \NATtwo is equal to \NATone
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    if k is equal to \NATone and it is wrong that l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      \NATone \NATless l
      \NATone \NATplus l \NATless k \NATplus l and \NATone \NATless \NATone \NATplus l
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone and l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      \NATone \NATless k
      k \NATplus \NATone \NATless k \NATplus l and \NATone \NATless k \NATplus \NATone
      falsity holds
    Qed.
    if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone and it is wrong that l is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      a is a natural number and b is a natural number and (k is equal to a \NATplus \NATone and l is equal to b \NATplus \NATone)
      Proof:
        it is wrong that k is equal to \NATzero and it is wrong that l is equal to \NATzero
      Qed.
      k is equal to a \NATplus \NATone and l is equal to b \NATplus \NATone
      \NATone \NATless k and \NATone \NATless l
      Proof:
        a is positive and b is positive
      Qed.
    Qed.
  Qed.
  n \NATplus \NATone is equal to m \NATplus l and m \NATplus l is equal to m \NATplus \NATzero and m \NATplus \NATzero is equal to m
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (if v1 \NATleq v0 and v0 \NATless v1 \NATplus \NATone then v1 is equal to v0)))
